<subSubSection pageId="216" pageNumber="217" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="216" pageNumber="217">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="216" pageNumber="217">Thirty-eight Neotropical species (Lorenz 2005: 58), of which one extends into southwestern North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="217" pageNumber="218" type="faunistic note">
<paragraph pageId="217" pageNumber="218">
<pageBreakToken pageId="217" pageNumber="218" start="start">Faunistic</pageBreakToken>
Note.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="217" pageNumber="218">
The Cuban 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dejean" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Brasiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="217" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Brasiella viridicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Dejean) is known in North America from a single specimen, probably a stray, collected in the Florida Keys in 1983 (Schiefer 2005: 551; Pearson et al. 2006: 151). The species is not considered here as a North American entity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
